<doc id="80220" wikidata="Q2524852" url="?curid=80220" title="Peleiades">
<text>Peleiades (Greek: , &quot;doves&quot;) were the sacred women of Zeus and the Mother Goddess, Dione, at the Oracle at Dodona. Pindar made a reference to the Pleiades as the &quot;peleiades&quot; a flock of doves, but the connection seems witty and poetical, rather than mythic. The chariot of Aphrodite was drawn by a flock of doves, however. A mythic element of a black dove that initiated the oracle at Dodona, which Herodotus was told in the 5th century BC may be an attempt to account for a folk etymology applied to the archaic name of the sacred women that no longer made sense (an aitiological myth). Perhaps the &quot;pel-&quot; element in their name was originally connected with &quot;black&quot; or &quot;muddy&quot; root elements in names like Peleus or Pelops and peliganes (Epirotian, Macedonian senators), Attic &quot;polios&quot;, Doric &quot;peleios&quot; grey, old, PIE *pel-, &quot;gray&quot;. Peleiades are often confused with the nymphs Pleiades.

